[00:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'What if you had all of the AI generative musical power of Sunno natively in a DAW, which means the ability to generate and edit your audio, change your lyrics, and even do cover songs. But it [music] goes further than that. Haven\'t you ever wanted to change out the voices in your'

[00:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Suno songs, maybe even add multiple voices? What about a choir? That\'s just scratching the surface. Welcome back to the channel where we discuss the creative uses of AI, and I am so excited about showing you the latest update from'

[00:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'A Studio. I\'m going to show you what\'s so freaking cool about it. If you\'re brand new to a studio, this is basically an AI based DAW that allows you to convert vocals into MIDI. And from there, the sky is the limit. You may be able to take your entire sunno workflow'

[00:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and bring it into a studio and immediately be able to do way more with it. So, let\'s take the basic functionality of Sunno, which is giving it a prompt and getting a song in a studio. The way you would do that is just rightclick anywhere on the screen. A little menu is going to pop up with AI'

[00:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'tools. Inspire me allows you to do exactly what we\'re talking about doing. Starting with a prompt, I\'d prompt it just like I would do. So I could do something very simple like Bflat blues riff traditional blues which is what I did here. I did not click instrumental.'

[01:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So it\'s going to generate some lyrics. And when I click on that it begins the generation process. And we wait just like we do with suno. Once we get a generation we like we can drag it right on into the timeline and begin to play with it. Now for this example I\'m going to use one I generated earlier. It\'s'

[01:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'basically the same idea. Blues riff. Here\'s what it sounds like &gt;&gt; down by the tracks where the old trains. &gt;&gt; For this example, I\'m going to show you'

[01:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'a feature called layering, which if you\'ve played with Sununo Studio, you may be familiar with. The idea is that you can create another layer of instrumentation on top of what has already been generated that will work along with it. So let\'s say for example here at the beginning'

[01:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'maybe I\'m thinking that sounds a little empty. I want something on there. We can start to play with layering ideas like for example maybe a piano. So what we'

[01:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'would do is on another track we would select the area where we want to generate that piano. So I\'m going to go ahead and just choose this first four measures here. I\'m going to right mouse click on AI tools. Click on add layer. And now we have a couple of options. Instrumental is like generating an'

[02:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'entire pseudo track with layers of instruments. Whereas, if you just want to add one instrument like we do now, we would click on the stem and sample loop and we would choose the most appropriate category. In this case, keyboard and instead of blues guitar riff, which was'

[02:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'one here before, I\'ll change it to laid-back piano riff and let that generate. So, now you can see that it\'s working on creating content here for these first four measures. Okay, let\'s see what it did. [music]'

